id="9ryIUTLkm2ush3Vq2dK9-66" value="<b>Time series feature tables</b><div style="text-align: left;"><ul><li>Examples of time-dependent features:&nbsp;time series data, event-based data, or time-aggregated data</li><li>When training a model, we must use only feature values up until the time of the observed target value</li><li>Time series feature tables include a timestamp column that ensures that each row in the training dataset represents the latest known feature values as of the row’s timestamp.</li><li>How point-in-time joining works:&nbsp;</li><ul><li>During FeatureLookup initialization, the feature table (with the timestamp column) and the `timestamp_lookup_key` column name from the labelled data (the "DataFrame") are specified. This tells the API that when the labelled data is fed later, look for the latest feature values from the timestamp column prior to the `timestamp_lookup_key` column.</li><li>During `FeatureEngineering.create_training_set()` invocation, it is provided with the DataFrame, and the lookup object above, and execute the logic.&nbsp;Databricks Feature Store retrieves the latest feature values prior to the timestamps specified in the DataFrame’s timestamp_lookup_key column and whose primary keys (excluding timestamp keys) match the values in the DataFrame’s lookup_key columns, or null if no such feature value exists.</li><li>During&nbsp; `FeatureEngineering.score_batch()`invocation, the input data to score must process the necessary ID and timestamp columns&nbsp;specified in the FeatureLookups of the training_set. If the input data has the same feature column (by name) as the feature table, the input data will be used instead of fetching&nbsp; values from the feature table.</li></ul></ul></div>" ul.li: Examples of time-dependent features: time series data, event-based data, or time-aggregated data
When training a model, we must use only feature values up until the time of the observed target value
Time series feature tables include a timestamp column that ensures that each row in the training dataset represents the latest known feature values as of the row’s timestamp.

During FeatureLookup initialization, the feature table (with the timestamp column) and the `timestamp_lookup_key` column name from the labelled data (the "DataFrame") are specified. This tells the API that when the labelled data is fed later, look for the latest feature values from the timestamp column prior to the `timestamp_lookup_key` column.

During `FeatureEngineering.create_training_set()` invocation, it is provided with the DataFrame, and the lookup object above, and execute the logic. Databricks Feature Store retrieves the latest feature values prior to the timestamps specified in the DataFrame’s timestamp_lookup_key column and whose primary keys (excluding timestamp keys) match the values in the DataFrame’s lookup_key columns, or null if no such feature value exists.

During `FeatureEngineering.score_batch()`invocation, the input data to score must process the necessary ID and timestamp columns specified in the FeatureLookups of the training_set. If the input data has the same feature column (by name) as the feature table, the input data will be used instead of fetching values from the feature table.
